Conclusion first: Astro 5's glob loader resolves relative base paths from process.cwd() at build time — not from the config file's location. When you build from a monorepo workspace root using pnpm --filter @seo-farm/oss-alternatives build, the working directory is the repository root, not apps/oss-alternatives. A relative path like ./content/per-alternative-takes silently resolves to a directory that doesn't exist, returns an empty collection, and your pages render as if no editorial content was ever written. No error. No warning. Just missing content.

What content collections are doing in this context

The Open Alternative To site generates one page per SaaS category — Notion alternatives, Slack alternatives, Linear alternatives. Each page follows the same template: GitHub repo data fetched by ETL, a Claude Haiku-generated intro, star counts, language tags, license information.

That uniformity is useful at launch. It becomes a liability once pages start getting indexed. Pages that don't differ in any editorially meaningful way are one step away from AdSense's scaled-content policy. For categories where I've used the software, I want to add a first-person take — something that reads as genuine evaluation rather than templated output.

Astro 5 content collections as an editorial layer fit this pattern well: they're typed, validated at build time, and getEntry() returns undefined for missing entries rather than throwing. Pages without a take render normally; pages with a take get an extra section automatically. No runtime cost, no per-page API call. The concept is the same as pipeline-aware content variants — encoding differentiation at build time rather than per request.

The problem is a subtle interaction between how the glob loader resolves paths and where a monorepo build runs from.

The configuration that looked correct

apps/oss-alternatives/src/content.config.ts, first version:

import { defineCollection, z } from "astro:content";
import { glob } from "astro/loaders";
const perAlternativeTakes = defineCollection({
loader: glob({
pattern: "**/*.md",
base: "./content/per-alternative-takes",
}),
schema: z.object({
saas_slug: z.string(),
author: z.string(),
last_reviewed: z.string(),
summary: z.string().max(200),
}),
});
export const collections = { "per-alternative-takes": perAlternativeTakes };

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

Locally, running astro build from apps/oss-alternatives/, this works. The editorial takes load. The pages render. The build exits zero.

The issue: locally you almost always cd apps/oss-alternatives && pnpm build. In CI, the GitHub Actions workflow runs pnpm --filter @seo-farm/oss-alternatives build from the workspace root. Different working directory. Same config file. Different behavior.

How the bug surfaces

When the glob loader can't find files matching base, it returns an empty collection. No error at build time. The Astro build completes successfully. The pages render — they just don't have editorial takes. If you're not specifically asserting that takes appear, you won't notice until a human checks.

In my case, I noticed during a manual spot-check. I'd written a take for the Notion alternatives page, pushed it, triggered a build, and loaded the live page. No editorial section. No build failure to investigate.

Diagnosis: add a temporary log to the page component, rebuild, watch the output.

// apps/oss-alternatives/src/pages/alternatives/[slug].astro
const takes = await getCollection("per-alternative-takes");
console.log("[debug] takes loaded:", takes.length);
// Output in CI: [debug] takes loaded: 0
// Output locally: [debug] takes loaded: 3

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

The collection returned zero entries in CI, three entries locally. Same code. Same files committed. Same Astro version. The only difference was the working directory when the build ran.

Tracing the Astro source: glob() calls path.resolve(options.base). path.resolve with a relative argument resolves against process.cwd(). In the GitHub Actions runner, process.cwd() is /home/runner/work/seo-farm/seo-farm — the workspace root. ./content/per-alternative-takes resolves to /home/runner/work/seo-farm/seo-farm/content/per-alternative-takes, which doesn't exist. The loader finds zero files and silently returns an empty array.

The fix: anchor every path to import.meta.url

The idiomatic fix in ES modules is import.meta.url:

import { defineCollection, z } from "astro:content";
import { glob } from "astro/loaders";
import { fileURLToPath } from "node:url";
// Resolves relative to this file — not relative to process.cwd().
const TAKES_DIR = fileURLToPath(
new URL("./content/per-alternative-takes", import.meta.url)
);
const perAlternativeTakes = defineCollection({
loader: glob({
pattern: "**/*.md",
base: TAKES_DIR,
}),
schema: z.object({
saas_slug: z.string(),
author: z.string(),
last_reviewed: z.string(),
summary: z.string().max(200),
}),
});

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

import.meta.url is the URL of the current module — always absolute, always pointing to the config file regardless of where the build was invoked. new URL('./content/...', import.meta.url) resolves the relative path against that module URL, and fileURLToPath() converts the result to an OS path string.

The resolved path looks like /home/runner/work/seo-farm/seo-farm/apps/oss-alternatives/src/content/per-alternative-takes — correct from any working directory.

This pattern is standard Node.js ESM. It's what the Node.js docs recommend for __dirname equivalents in ESM, where __dirname is no longer available. For Astro config files, which are always ES modules, it's the safe default.

The generateId fix I added at the same time

While I was in the config file, I noticed a second latent issue: by default, the glob loader uses a file's slug: frontmatter field as its entry ID if present, falling back to the filename stem. The editorial take files use saas_slug: (the binding key for the page), not slug: — but a future author copying a template might include slug: by mistake.

The page component uses take.id === saas.slug as the lookup invariant. If a take file's frontmatter slug: field overrides its ID to something unexpected, the take silently detaches from its page. Another silent failure, same category as the path issue.

The fix is generateId:

loader: glob({
pattern: "**/*.md",
base: TAKES_DIR,
generateId: ({ entry }) => entry.replace(/\.md$/i, ""),
}),

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

Now the filename is always the authoritative ID. Frontmatter can't override it. A rename is immediately visible because the ID no longer matches saas.slug. The schema still validates saas_slug: as a required field — if you rename the file but forget to update frontmatter, the build fails at schema validation rather than silently serving the wrong take.

Testing this across build contexts

The practical lesson here is that content collection behavior can diverge between local and CI builds when your working directory differs. A few things I now do:

Always run the integration build from workspace root in local smoke tests:

# From the repository root — matches CI working directory
pnpm --filter @seo-farm/oss-alternatives build 2>&1 | grep -E "(error|warn|takes|collection)"

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

Running from the app directory can mask this class of bug entirely. I added this as a reminder to my local pre-push checklist.

Add a collection health assertion to the page component:

// In alternatives/[slug].astro, during dev only
if (import.meta.env.DEV) {
const all = await getCollection("per-alternative-takes");
if (all.length === 0) {
throw new Error("per-alternative-takes collection is empty — check glob base path");
}
}

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

This throws during development builds if the collection is empty, catching the regression before it ships. In production builds import.meta.env.DEV is false so there's no overhead.

Extend the post-deploy check:

The three post-deploy checks I run after every Cloudflare Pages build include a page-content assertion. I added one that fetches an alternatives page where I know a take exists and checks that the editorial section is present in the response HTML. It's a two-line check that would have caught this regression in minutes.

The broader pattern: Astro surprises in monorepos

This is the second place I've hit Astro behavior that differs silently between local and CI builds. The first was @astrojs/sitemap generating /sitemap-0.xml instead of /sitemap-index.xml on small sites — behavior that depended on total page count, which differed between the two build contexts.

The pattern across both cases: Astro's defaults are designed around single-app builds run from the app directory. In a monorepo where astro build runs from a different working directory, implicit path resolution and page-count-dependent behavior can silently produce wrong results. Nothing errors. The build exits zero. You ship wrong output.

My current heuristic: any file reference that isn't a TypeScript import statement should use import.meta.url-anchored resolution. Any Astro behavior that depends on directory contents or page counts should be tested from the same working directory as CI. The content quality gate I built for articles uses this principle explicitly — check assumptions rather than trust that silence equals success.

The E-EAT transparency work added a methodology page that documents content sourcing. The editorial takes layer sits above the programmatic three-tier content quality ladder. Both are worth nothing if the content collection silently returns empty and takes never render.

What I'd do differently starting over

Two changes:

Abolish all relative file paths in Astro config. Every path that points outside the current file should use fileURLToPath(new URL(..., import.meta.url)). There's no downside — it's slightly more verbose and eliminates an entire class of monorepo build surprises. I've started applying this to every new Astro project without thinking about it.

Add a content collection smoke test to CI. A 10-line script that builds the app and asserts collection sizes against expected minimums would have caught this immediately. Not a full E2E test — just getCollection() calls with assertions, run after build. If the collection count is zero and you expected non-zero, that's a hard failure. The ambiguity between "no editorial takes exist" and "editorial takes exist but the loader can't find them" needs to be resolved at CI time, not after the fact in production.

FAQ

Why doesn't the glob loader throw if the base path doesn't exist?

Current Astro behavior (5.x) treats a missing directory as returning zero files — consistent with how many file-system APIs handle missing paths. The argument for a warning is that this silent failure mode is very hard to diagnose. I'd prefer an explicit opt-in: glob({ base, required: true }) that throws if zero files match. As of writing, no such option exists.

Does this affect all Astro loaders or just glob?

I hit it with glob. The file loader takes a single file path and is more likely to surface an error on a missing file, though I haven't verified that across all failure modes. Custom loaders handle path resolution however their author implemented it.

Can I use process.cwd() instead of import.meta.url?

No — that has the same problem. process.cwd() depends on where you invoke the build, not where the file lives. Use import.meta.url.

Does this affect projects where astro build always runs from the app directory?

If your cwd always matches the config file's directory, relative paths work as expected. The bug only manifests when they differ — which is the common case for monorepos, Turborepo builds, Nx builds, or any build orchestrator that invokes Astro from a parent directory.

